The 28-year-old chef, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in the staircase of a local shopping mall this week.
However, the victim's brother says that he can't imagine someone who would like to hurt him, noting: "Finally, things were going well."
"The body found at Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning was identified as 28-year-old San Francisco resident Frank Galicia," San Francisco's forensics office said.
The San Francisco Police Department reports that the death was classified as murder and the investigation is ongoing.
The victim's brother, Louis Galicia, told ABC's KGO channel in San Francisco that Frank, a former Boston-based job as a dream job as a chef at San Francisco's Sons & Daughters, six months ago.
A spokesman for Sons & Daughters said they were "shocked and depressed" by his death.
"We are a small team that works as a friendly family and will be very missed," he said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank's family and friends during this difficult period.
Luis Galicia said that Frank first stayed at the hostels, but recently "Finally, things were going to the same place."
"He found an apartment, he was dating a girl," Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said that he could not imagine someone who would like to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good soul and a great heart.
His way of communion with his family was always to prepare us some dish, to prepare us dinner," said Louis Galicia.
He never wanted to be involved in any quarrel.
He was a brother who was sailing along the line.
"With all the bad things that happen to this world, it was the unheavy diamond that shone brightly every day," he said.
