At a court hearing this week, the Calais authorities said that the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 homemade shops where people inside the camp sell goods from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer to cut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simplest meals for several euros in homemade restaurants.
Calais Prefecture said that these places should be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and sanitation.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, saying that the free dishes offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not provide enough food for the growing number in the camp.
They said that homemade shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
Lille's court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel people managing 72 homemade shops, but said that the problems of Calais' prefecture "were fully understood."
Judge Jean-Francois Molla said that the groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much greater role than just feeding people who "live in extremely shaky conditions."
He said that the space provided calm points of meeting between refugees and volunteers.
One of the places that was threatened with demolition was the Jungle Children's Cafe, which does not work for profit and offers 200 lunches a day, English and French language classes and asylum counseling for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170,000 people signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
The letter sent to the Guardian stated that its closure "would have been a disaster for these children, some of whom are under eight years old."
Two charities, aid to the refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants on Friday estimated that the number in the Jungle camp grew and exceeded 9,000 people in history - the highest in history - after a sharp increase in new arrivals during the summer.
