The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
A UN Special Commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the UN special envoy for Syria, Steffan de Mistura, believes that the fact of what happened is undeniable.
Similar statements were made on the eve of the third round of intra-Syrian talks, which are due to begin in late August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack using toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where the Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, the aircraft dropped bombs with a poisonous substance, but in Moscow these charges called a dump.
Later, the Russian Ministry of Defense accused the opposition group "Harakat Nur al-Din al-Zinky" in the incident.
It soon became known that the bombs filled with toxic gas were two.
This was confirmed by the BBC by one of the victims.
"A few minutes later, I felt the smell of gas, the beginning to burn my eyes, it became difficult to breathe," the eyewitness said.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be regarded as a war crime.
The UN Special Envoy for Syria Staffan de Mistura told reporters: "There is a lot of evidence that this really happened."
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is prescribed in the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015, human rights activists recorded 35 cases of use of chlorine by the Syrian army against the "moderate opposition."
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that shelling of its areas is carried out daily, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a "humanitarian pause" in military operations.
The current three-hour lull regime in the organization is considered "insufficient to help nearly 2 million civilians trapped."
Staffan de Mistura Humanitarian Adviser Jan Egeland said a 48-hour ceasefire would be required to deliver aid to the city and evacuate sick and wounded people every week.
"We have to send bulk cargo from a column of trucks in the area where the roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain, mined," - said Mr. Egeland. "But the Russian delegation has confirmed its readiness to sit with us at the negotiating table."
Consultations in Geneva between U.S. and Russian representatives on the establishment of a "humanitarian pause" continue.
How Russia opened "humanitarian windows" in Aleppo.
In the face of the ongoing battle for Aleppo - the second largest Syrian city - Russia on August 11 announced the introduction of a three-hour cessation of hostilities, which will operate daily from Thursday.
The creation of "humanitarian windows" is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and basic necessities to the city.
The decision of the Russian Defense Ministry was made against the background of increasing international pressure on Moscow with the demand to curtail the military operation and contribute to the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand killed four people.
Several explosions exploded in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed, 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua-Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, Russians among them are not.
None of the terrorist groups have so far taken responsibility for the incident, but the Ministry of Internal Affairs of the country hastened to say that the Islamists were not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data of the local police, the scale and features of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military leaders.
The attacks took place at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in Phuket and Hua Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the arrival of the military junta to power in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, 14 million people have already visited the country, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks have already been detained, police colonel Chrisan Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about the goals, he added, but the Ministry of Internal Affairs of the country "is confident that they are not associated with international extremist groups."
It is too early to draw conclusions, Mr. Patanacharoen said. the
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact, these are local sabotage, and we are trying to identify the identities of those behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Queen Sikerit of Thailand.
The Thai junta considers the defense of the monarchy one of its main priorities, so the incident is likely to be directed against it.
According to police general Sithichhai Srisopacharanate, the bombs were detonated remotely with a half-hour difference.
They were hidden inside trees on busy streets filled with dining in restaurants by tourists.
It is already known that one of the four dead was a Thai girl who traded street food.
The identities of the other victims are still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign countries.
According to the Royal Thai Police, including four German citizens, three Dutch nationals, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of the Federal Tourism Service reported.
Local experts also attribute the explosions to the referendum held on August 7, at which 61.4% of the country's population supported the draft new constitution.
It was prepared by the Commission for the Drafting of the Constitution, appointed by the military junta.
The voters needed to decide whether they supported the system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and had a significant role in the election of the country's prime minister.
The new system was adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
We will remind, on May 22, 2014 in Thailand there was a military coup led by the commander of the army of the country Prayuth Chan-Ocha.
This step, he said, the army was prompted by an ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed a curfew and censorship, dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok was in a state of emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra, announced a state of emergency in Bangkok and adjacent provinces in January 2014.
The regime lasted 60 days.
Two explosions occurred in Bangkok.
In January 2014, in the center of Bangkok, at the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, two explosions occurred, as a result of which 28 people were injured, five of them were in critical condition.
The explosions were made by unknown on motorcycles.
The authorities increased security measures in the capital and attracted military forces to protect the demonstrators.
In the Dry Log began the development of conditions.
As it became known "Kommersant," the government was asked to agree on the draft conditions for the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold ore deposit, while maintaining two key restrictions.
It is proposed to prevent a company where 25% or more belongs to foreigners, and those applicants whose capital will not be at least 25% of state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewinter the conditions, noting that many players do not risk taking up a difficult and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August and held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and conditions of the auction for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia Sukhoi Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), said two sources "Kommersant," familiar with the situation.
The project was introduced on Wednesday evening, one of them clarifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project was submitted to the government.
The representative of the supervisory subsoil use of Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin told Kommersant that the official's office has not yet received the project.
"The auction can be announced in August, immediately after the issuance of the order of the government, and taking into account the time frame for the collection of applications of potential participants (at least 45 days) the tender may take place in October," the Ministry of Natural Resources said.
According to Kommersant, the project retains two key requirements for potential participants, prescribed in the version, which was sent for approval to the ministries and FOIVs in July (there is a "Kommersant").
The first is the presence in the capital of applicants at least 25% of state participation.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 about foreign investments in strategic societies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft, as already written "Kommersant" on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of the shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship - can not allow the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since the Dry Log belongs to the depths of federal significance (stocks of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project "contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies," but refused to comment on the details before the government's order.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the auction was put forward by the Irkutsk region, said in December 2015 "Kommersant" in the Ministry of Natural Resources and confirmed later by the Governor of the region Sergey Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor Sergei Eroschenko, "who had agreements on investment projects with Rostec."
Who lobbied the restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors "Kommersant" do not specify.
"But this is in the spirit of the time: not to give control in the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions," - says the interlocutor of "Kommersant," familiar with the preparation of the auction.
The head of the Ministry of Natural Resources Sergey Donskoy on August 1 said that foreigners "can go to the consortium" if the applicants attract them "as a financial structure, technological partners."
The interlocutors of "Kommersant" believe it is unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukhoi Log in the industry is a consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation PJSC Polyus, controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostec.
As Kommersant wrote, in July, the partners created the joint venture "SPL Gold," where Polyus has 51% of the shares, the structure of "Rostec" RT-GR - 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, Polyus said that "certainly, they are interested in this asset" and have all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the conditions," - added in the "Polyus."
ALROSA may participate in the auction, but the decision is with the government of the Russian Federation, Kommersant sources said.
The possibility of participation in the development of the Sukhoi Log was stated by the Russian GV Gold and the Canadian Kinross, which is developing assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of gold industry of the Russian Federation Sergey Kashuba in December 2015 estimated "Kommersant" investments in Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
Most potential applicants scare away not only the amount of investment, but also the complexity of the project: you need serious additional exploration of reserves and technology of work with complex ores, explain the interlocutors of "Kommersant" in the industry.
