Yesterday, the DUM plenum ordered its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatar in order to force young Tatars to "study their native language."
The administration declares that it "in no case infringes" the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some mosques, Kazan complain that the Tatar language is not understood by up to 60% of parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
The imams fear that their sermons in the Tatar "will not reach the whole audience."
Yesterday, the plenum of the DUM of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
As stated by the mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars to "study their native language."
"For those who say that "heavy," in every large mosque we intend to organize lessons of the Tatar language absolutely free," - said Mr. Samigullin.
He added that "the decision has already entered into force" and today in all mosques the sermon "must be in the Tatar language."
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
The imam, who does not speak well in plainclothes, "can prepare thoroughly on them."
The DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, in the areas of Friday sermons are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques previously used mainly Russian.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaev mosque, Zakabannaya and "Eniler."
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the leadership sets the task that all students speak both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no question of infringement of non-Atam Muslims," Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, explaining that the preaching itself "is not a mandatory, the main part of the prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will remain in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of displacing the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar languages, such as Uzbek or Tajik, according to him, are not used in the preaching in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported in the Executive Committee of the World Congress of Tatars (VKT).
