Former FSIN director put on trial
The Moscow prosecutor's office approved the indictment on the criminal case investigated by the GSU of the TFR on the theft of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
Before the court will be the former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy, who caused the FSIN damage in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Metropolitan Prosecutor's Office sent a criminal case against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the Federal State Penitentiary Service and the Center for Information and Technical Support and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service (FSUE CITOS) Viktor Determinov.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of the GSU TFR in Moscow. 3 st. 285 Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, entailing grave consequences), 4 st. 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed with the use of their official position, as part of an organized group, in an especially large amount).
In addition, Krivolapov is accused by the hour. 1 st. 222 RF Criminal Code (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the TFR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole from the state treasury the budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the company controlled by him FSUE CITOS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including "electronic bracelets," and implemented at prices overestimated several times.
Despite the fact that FSUE CITOS did not have production equipment, buildings, structures for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a completed cycle of production of "electronic bracelets," five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles turned out to be on the accounts of the Samara branch of FSUE, of which 1.2 billion rubles. It was abducted.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. The cashed funds were personally received by Mr. Reimer in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case against which was allocated to a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolaappov, who participated in the machinations, was found of unknown origin cartridges for the award pistol, which allowed him to bring additional charges.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN to the accused filed a claim for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Footballer Hakan Shukur is suspected of involvement in the putsch.
The Turkish authorities issued a warrant for the arrest of the former football player, and then a member of Parliament Hakan Shukur and conducted searches in two houses of his family.
The star of Turkish football of the 1990s - early 2000s striker Hakan Shukur is wanted by the authorities of the country in connection with the attempted coup d'etat that took place last month.
Forward, who ended his sports career in 2008, is accused of belonging to an "armed terrorist group."
We are talking about the movement "Hizmet" - a society associated with the famous Turkish religious figure and opposition leader Fethullah Gulen.
It is his President Erdogan who considers the organizer of the attempted military coup, which occurred on July 15.
Fethullah Gulen resides in the United States, and the Turkish authorities are demanding his extradition.
According to local media, today a warrant for the arrest of Hakan Shukur was issued, the police have already conducted searches in two houses that belong to the family of the former football player.
According to investigators, the organization of Fethullah Gulen, in addition to the Hakan Shukur himself, included his father.
However, neither the most former football player nor his relatives were there.
He and his family now live in the United States.
As a footballer, Hakan Shukuyur defended the colors of several Turkish clubs and played for the national team.
He spent most of his career at Galatasaray.
The list of foreign clubs includes the Italian Torino, Inter and Palermo, as well as English Blackburn.
He didn't spend more than one season in any of them.
Hakan Shukur remains the most successful striker of the national team of Turkey: in his asset 112 matches for the national team and 51 goals scored.
In 2013, Hakan Shukuur resigned from his deputy's office due to a corruption investigation around Erdogan's party and his immediate entourage.
