The Russian Copper Company (RMC) is ready to take on social responsibility and pay more attention to the environmental aspects of its business.
This is confirmed, for example, by the fact that the RDK took up the modernization of one of the oldest and most environmentally "dirty" enterprises of the country - the Karabash copper smelting plant.
The Karabash copper smelter was founded by the English joint stock company headed by Leslie Urquord in 1910.
In Soviet times, it was a significant industrial enterprise for the country's economy, and it actually ensured the vital activity of the whole city.
However, in the 1990s, due to financial problems, production was halted, which led to serious social problems in Karabash.
