"Generation Protests" in Ethiopia, a long ago U.S. ally
The Fierce Protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced a fierce opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally injured in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the verge of splitting?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a firm ally of the West with a rapidly developing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
In the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets demanding radical political change.
According to human rights defenders, the Government's response was brutal.
Eyewitnesses claimed that police officers had shot and killed dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Videos from the protest sites, allegedly shot at the end of last year or earlier this year, show security officers beating young people with sticks when they put their hands on the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"It has always been difficult to keep this country from disintegrating, and it will continue to be even more difficult," said Rashid Abdi, head of the African Horn project in the international crisis group.
Ethiopia is Africa's second-centred country after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with the Ethiopians to deal with terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
Ethiopia's economy is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets are usually quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy - human rights organizations constantly mention government repressions - the opposition on the territory of the state was stopped, due to the fact that dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, killed or expelled to remote deserts.
But that could change.
"If people are constantly suppressed and left no option other than to protest, a revolt will rise," said Seyum Teshome, a university lecturer in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use, to the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After widely criticizing the elections last year, the government party and its allies completely supplanted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are growing; the struggle for this uncertain, controversial border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit unrest and re-equip.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, boiling in the depths of the soul for several years, flash now.
The first, it would seem, completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians were able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones became commonplace, and the Internet service became better.
Even when the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as is often the case, especially during the protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized for the protests.
The second is that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oromo and Amhara are not natural allies.
Over the centuries, Amhara from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas.
But it's also changing.
"We will act together under a single level," Moluta Gemechu, leader of Oromo, told Molat.
The largest protests took place in the areas of Amhara and Oromo.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which constitutes about 6 percent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years, until his death from an unknown disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts claim that he especially skillfully recognized the first signals of discontent and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
"The current regime lacks common sense," Abdi, an analyst at conflict situations, said.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desaleni, appeared out of nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the confidence of the security services controlled by the Tigray.
Many fear that as a result, this will lead to even more bloodshed.
Ethiopia last experienced such unrest in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said were apparently elections that the government had spurred and then forged the results.
In the ensuing repression, many Protestants were killed, albeit in smaller numbers than the last months, and this period of unrest went relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed appreciation to Ethiopia's leaders for the far-sighted infrastructure development, such as a new long-distance train and significant advances in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this did not stop the growth of internal dissatisfaction with the Ethiopian government.
It takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, the city in Amhar, attacked Tigray-owned businesses, and anti-Tyligai hate on social media is becoming comprehensive.
Analysts say the protesters are putting the United States and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighbouring Somalia, although it recently announced it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, it does not want its ally to lose power in an already unstable region.
"And on this stretched rope will be difficult to pass," Abdi said.
