Condoms with chili powder and fireworks increase protection of Tanzanian elephants
Environmental protection fighters in Tanzania are using an unconventional way to prevent elephants from wandering in populated areas - throwing condoms filled with chili powder.
The method proved effective, and the Honeyguide Foundation, which came to mind this idea a few years ago, together with the American Committee for the Conservation of Nature took over its promotion, training volunteers in the villages of northern Tanzania to use a non-violent, four-step-foot-based way to protect their homes and sobs without harming animals.
Previously, many people used spears to protect themselves.
On Friday, there will be World Elephant Day dedicated to animal protection.
"Since we've invented the toolkit ... we've seen a change in attitudes within these communities, making them much more confident that they can keep elephants on their fields without harming elephants," said Honeyguide chief executive Damian Bell.
The first two steps are to ignite the torch in front of an elephant that broke the border and signaling with an horn.
If it is not possible to scare off, the so-called "cook of chili" is thrown away.
Chili powder mixed with the soil is placed with a clap in a condom, and its end is twisted, only the wick remains outside.
When igniting the condom, it bursts with a rumbling, spraying the fine dust of chili powder in the air.
One breath is usually enough to turn the elephant in the other direction.
The extreme measure is a launcher that shoots Roman candles into the air, producing a loud, bright explosion.
