Climate model of NASA: Venus was once inhabited
Venus may have once been habitable, according to estimates of a new climate model by NASA.
Scientists from the Goddard Institute for the Study of the Earthrad developed a model for the study of Venus's past, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, with its hot anhydrous surface and an atmosphere oversaturated with carbon dioxide, could someday have conditions like the Earth's.
Scientists previously assumed that the small speed of rotation of Venus was due to its dense atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus could probably have a sparse atmosphere like the earth, and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably more arid regions on the planet than on Earth, but it once had enough water and geographical variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus was also the benefit of the sun, which was 30 percent dimmer.
"According to the GISS model, Venus's slow rotation puts it on the daytime side of the sun for almost two months at one time," GISS scientist Anthony Del Henio explained in a press.
This warms the planet's surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella that protects the planet's surface from a substantial part of solar heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are a few degrees colder than they are on Earth today.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development that previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Although Venus may have been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned out by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen faded, only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect remained - that is, Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
