Kepler measures the speed of star rotation in the Pleiades cluster
The last mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of the rotational speeds of stars included in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data help astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, and how the rotation periods are correlated with the formation of planets.
"We hope that by matching our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system," said Louise Riball, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Pleiades is found 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They rotate as fast as they will never be.
At their peak rotation speeds, these adult-growing stars eject large amounts of stellar wind.
Traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds exert a inhibitory action on the stars.
As the stars age, its speed of rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotation speed of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable stellar spots, such as sunspots.
The newest velocity catalog suggests that more massive stars orbit more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares the stars with dancers: larger make pirouettes more slowly than smaller ones.
"In the "ballet" of the Pleiades, we see that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, whereas those that rotate faster usually refer to very light stars," Riball said.
Since the Plelyad cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory to match the properties of stars with rotational speeds.
"The star cluster of the Pleiades provides a starting point for theoretical models of rotation of stars, both younger and older," Riball said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why stars slow down the speed of their rotation and hang their "dance shoes" on the nail, figuratively speaking.
Riball and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the velocities of the Pleiades in three new articles, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
