Many have heard about the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest golden objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps it was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand with a total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one burial, known as "the grave number 43," was extracted 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the world's oldest gold may soon go to a non-descript bead found by archaeologists in July this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yunacite.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tel Yunacitet is located far from the sea, near the village of Yunatite of the Pazardzhik district.
The bead is a golden strip rolled in a ring.
Yavor Boyajiev, the head of the Tulle Yunacit excavations, dated the find 4600 BC and stated that she was older than Varna's gold for at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date from about the same period, 4600-4200 years. before our era.
Technologies that allow you to date the metal with impeccable accuracy does not exist at present.
What is the confidence in which gold is older?
Obviously, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: "I am quite sure that Yunatit's gold is older than Varna's gold."
This is a find of extreme importance: it's a tiny object in sight, but it's big enough to take a proper place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as again and more thoroughly study the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bead with the highest possible accuracy.
The location explains a lot of things.
Tel Yunacite is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Currently, Tell Yunacite is considered the oldest "city" of Europe.
Tellle was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7th millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, the processing of metals, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry, developed rapidly in this region.
In the national historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkano-Karpatik metallurgical province.
In the 5 millennium BC, urban-type settlements began to arise around the centers of metalworking.
They are now known as the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunacite is perhaps the oldest, as artifacts 4900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yunakit a prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
"This place is a thousand years older than Sumer," Boyajiev says, referring to the generally accepted view that urban culture originated in the south of Mesopotamia - modern Iraq.
There were the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
The excavations of Telle Yunakte have been underway since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall were found, which once reached three meters in height.
Little has survived from houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish the streets, public buildings, dense buildings, "business center" and residential areas.
The tel of Yunakite is often called the "bird city": dozens of clay figurines of birds were found here.
All the birds are depicted at rest, hence it was suggested that they were not decorative objects, but an object of local cult.
The "bird's city" was destroyed around 4100 BC - arguably Indo-European tribes that came from the northeast.
The nomads had no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
The three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a brutal massacre: inside the houses were found the remains of old people, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by axes.
New findings and new facts appear annually, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the "lost" first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "Gold of Varna," found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that Varna's gold luxury had to be preceded by something - something like a tiny golden bead created in Tella Yunacite.
